items.title: Clitocybe spp.
items.content_text: Clitocybe brunneoceracea. Seen on wood near Lerderderg River.

items.title: Gymnopilus eucalyptorum
items.content_text: Small saprophyte found on large logs. Cap to 20mm. Stem has a white bloom.

items.title: Gymnopilus spp.
items.content_text: Gymnopilus austropicreus. (B.J.Rees) Small saprophyte often on large logs. Cap to 30mm. Gates p83.

items.title: Clitopilus spp.
items.content_text: Small fan shaped species that is found on rocks growing with mosses. Cap to 5mm. Gates p42. Clitopilus kamaka . J.A. Cooper. Spore print Brownish pink.

items.title: Hebeloma victoriense
items.content_text: Mycorrhizal. Found Bushland reserve.Pink spore on fibrils.

items.title: Cortinarius spp.
items.content_text: Yellow sp with some purple hues. Unknown to me.

items.title: Podoserpula pusio
items.content_text: On wood an old stump close to, the ground. Close to Lerderderg river.

items.title: Simocybe phlebophora
items.content_text: Small Mycena like species usually on fallen wood or stumps. The Khaki colored cap has a layer of gell under the outer skin causing a wrinkled appearance. Cal to 40mm.

items.title: Singerocybe clitocyboides
items.content_text: Widespread species that reaches into dry woodland where specimens are usually small to 30mm. Seen in Long Forest.

items.title: Cortinarius spp.
items.content_text: Cortinarius sp. (cap to 30mm) probable unnamed Found in the Dry woodland of Long Forest.

items.title: Panus spp.
items.content_text: Panus fasciatus or Lentinus fasciatus. The former is preferred. Found in dry woodland usually decomposing fallen wood from underneath probable where moisture collects. Seen in Long Forest.

items.title: Dacrymyces spp.
items.content_text: Small jelly balls to about 5mm diam. A reasonable fit for Dacrymyces aff stillatus. Found on a wet log with Calocera sp.

items.title: Cortinarius austrocyanites
items.content_text: Gates P49. Dark purplish cap with brown fibrils. The gills are sky blue colored untill becoming redbrown with ripening spore. Seen in the upper reaches of the Campaspe River.

items.title: Gymnogaster boletoides
items.content_text: Bolete truffle. Seen several times near the Sheoaks picnic area. Aprox 2 cm diam Not often found.
